  49 class _Nothing(object):
  50     """
  51     Sentinel class to indicate the lack of a value when ``None`` is ambiguous.
  52 
  53     ``_Nothing`` is a singleton. There is only ever one of it.
  54     """
  55 
  56     _singleton = None
  57 
  58     def __new__(cls):
  59         if _Nothing._singleton is None:
  60             _Nothing._singleton = super(_Nothing, cls).__new__(cls)
  61         return _Nothing._singleton
  62 
  63     def __repr__(self):
  64         return "NOTHING"

  73 def attrib(
  74     default=NOTHING,
  75     validator=None,
  76     repr=True,
  77     cmp=None,
  78     hash=None,
  79     init=True,
  80     metadata=None,
  81     type=None,
  82     converter=None,
  83     factory=None,
  84     kw_only=False,
  85     eq=None,
  86     order=None,
  87 ):
  88     """
  89     Create a new attribute on a class.
  90 
  91     ..  warning::
  92 
  93         Does *not* do anything unless the class is also decorated with
  94         `attr.s`!
  95 
  96     :param default: A value that is used if an ``attrs``-generated ``__init__``
  97         is used and no value is passed while instantiating or the attribute is
  98         excluded using ``init=False``.
  99 
 100         If the value is an instance of `Factory`, its callable will be
 101         used to construct a new value (useful for mutable data types like lists
 102         or dicts).
 103 
 104         If a default is not set (or set manually to ``attr.NOTHING``), a value
 105         *must* be supplied when instantiating; otherwise a `TypeError`
 106         will be raised.
 107 
 108         The default can also be set using decorator notation as shown below.
 109 
 110     :type default: Any value
 111 
 112     :param callable factory: Syntactic sugar for
 113         ``default=attr.Factory(callable)``.
 114 
 115     :param validator: `callable` that is called by ``attrs``-generated
 116         ``__init__`` methods after the instance has been initialized.  They
 117         receive the initialized instance, the `Attribute`, and the
 118         passed value.
 119 
 120         The return value is *not* inspected so the validator has to throw an
 121         exception itself.
 122 
 123         If a ``list`` is passed, its items are treated as validators and must
 124         all pass.
 125 
 126         Validators can be globally disabled and re-enabled using
 127         `get_run_validators`.
 128 
 129         The validator can also be set using decorator notation as shown below.
 130 
 131     :type validator: ``callable`` or a ``list`` of ``callable``\\ s.
 132 
 133     :param repr: Include this attribute in the generated ``__repr__``
 134         method. If ``True``, include the attribute; if ``False``, omit it. By
 135         default, the built-in ``repr()`` function is used. To override how the
 136         attribute value is formatted, pass a ``callable`` that takes a single
 137         value and returns a string. Note that the resulting string is used
 138         as-is, i.e. it will be used directly *instead* of calling ``repr()``
 139         (the default).
 140     :type repr: a ``bool`` or a ``callable`` to use a custom function.
 141     :param bool eq: If ``True`` (default), include this attribute in the
 142         generated ``__eq__`` and ``__ne__`` methods that check two instances
 143         for equality.
 144     :param bool order: If ``True`` (default), include this attributes in the
 145         generated ``__lt__``, ``__le__``, ``__gt__`` and ``__ge__`` methods.
 146     :param bool cmp: Setting to ``True`` is equivalent to setting ``eq=True,
 147         order=True``. Deprecated in favor of *eq* and *order*.
 148     :param hash: Include this attribute in the generated ``__hash__``
 149         method.  If ``None`` (default), mirror *eq*'s value.  This is the
 150         correct behavior according the Python spec.  Setting this value to
 151         anything else than ``None`` is *discouraged*.
 152     :type hash: ``bool`` or ``None``
 153     :param bool init: Include this attribute in the generated ``__init__``
 154         method.  It is possible to set this to ``False`` and set a default
 155         value.  In that case this attributed is unconditionally initialized
 156         with the specified default value or factory.
 157     :param callable converter: `callable` that is called by
 158         ``attrs``-generated ``__init__`` methods to converter attribute's value
 159         to the desired format.  It is given the passed-in value, and the
 160         returned value will be used as the new value of the attribute.  The
 161         value is converted before being passed to the validator, if any.
 162     :param metadata: An arbitrary mapping, to be used by third-party
 163         components.  See `extending_metadata`.
 164     :param type: The type of the attribute.  In Python 3.6 or greater, the
 165         preferred method to specify the type is using a variable annotation
 166         (see `PEP 526 <https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0526/>`_).
 167         This argument is provided for backward compatibility.
 168         Regardless of the approach used, the type will be stored on
 169         ``Attribute.type``.
 170 
 171         Please note that ``attrs`` doesn't do anything with this metadata by
 172         itself. You can use it as part of your own code or for
 173         `static type checking <types>`.
 174     :param kw_only: Make this attribute keyword-only (Python 3+)
 175         in the generated ``__init__`` (if ``init`` is ``False``, this
 176         parameter is ignored).
 177 
 178     .. versionadded:: 15.2.0 *convert*
 179     .. versionadded:: 16.3.0 *metadata*
 180     .. versionchanged:: 17.1.0 *validator* can be a ``list`` now.
 181     .. versionchanged:: 17.1.0
 182        *hash* is ``None`` and therefore mirrors *eq* by default.
 183     .. versionadded:: 17.3.0 *type*
 184     .. deprecated:: 17.4.0 *convert*
 185     .. versionadded:: 17.4.0 *converter* as a replacement for the deprecated
 186        *convert* to achieve consistency with other noun-based arguments.
 187     .. versionadded:: 18.1.0
 188        ``factory=f`` is syntactic sugar for ``default=attr.Factory(f)``.
 189     .. versionadded:: 18.2.0 *kw_only*
 190     .. versionchanged:: 19.2.0 *convert* keyword argument removed
 191     .. versionchanged:: 19.2.0 *repr* also accepts a custom callable.
 192     .. deprecated:: 19.2.0 *cmp* Removal on or after 2021-06-01.
 193     .. versionadded:: 19.2.0 *eq* and *order*
 194     """
 195     eq, order = _determine_eq_order(cmp, eq, order)
 196 
 197     if hash is not None and hash is not True and hash is not False:
 198         raise TypeError(
 199             "Invalid value for hash.  Must be True, False, or None."
 200         )
 201 
 202     if factory is not None:
 203         if default is not NOTHING:
 204             raise ValueError(
 205                 "The `default` and `factory` arguments are mutually "
 206                 "exclusive."
 207             )
 208         if not callable(factory):
 209             raise ValueError("The `factory` argument must be a callable.")
 210         default = Factory(factory)
 211 
 212     if metadata is None:
 213         metadata = {}
 214 
 215     return _CountingAttr(
 216         default=default,
 217         validator=validator,
 218         repr=repr,
 219         cmp=None,
 220         hash=hash,
 221         init=init,
 222         converter=converter,
 223         metadata=metadata,
 224         type=type,
 225         kw_only=kw_only,
 226         eq=eq,
 227         order=order,
 228     )

 231 def _make_attr_tuple_class(cls_name, attr_names):
 232     """
 233     Create a tuple subclass to hold `Attribute`s for an `attrs` class.
 234 
 235     The subclass is a bare tuple with properties for names.
 236 
 237     class MyClassAttributes(tuple):
 238         __slots__ = ()
 239         x = property(itemgetter(0))
 240     """
 241     attr_class_name = "{}Attributes".format(cls_name)
 242     attr_class_template = [
 243         "class {}(tuple):".format(attr_class_name),
 244         "    __slots__ = ()",
 245     ]
 246     if attr_names:
 247         for i, attr_name in enumerate(attr_names):
 248             attr_class_template.append(
 249                 _tuple_property_pat.format(index=i, attr_name=attr_name)
 250             )
 251     else:
 252         attr_class_template.append("    pass")
 253     globs = {"_attrs_itemgetter": itemgetter, "_attrs_property": property}
 254     eval(compile("\n".join(attr_class_template), "", "exec"), globs)
 255 
 256     return globs[attr_class_name]

 274 def _is_class_var(annot):
 275     """
 276     Check whether *annot* is a typing.ClassVar.
 277 
 278     The string comparison hack is used to avoid evaluating all string
 279     annotations which would put attrs-based classes at a performance
 280     disadvantage compared to plain old classes.
 281     """
 282     return str(annot).startswith(_classvar_prefixes)

 285 def _get_annotations(cls):
 286     """
 287     Get annotations for *cls*.
 288     """
 289     anns = getattr(cls, "__annotations__", None)
 290     if anns is None:
 291         return {}
 292 
 293     # Verify that the annotations aren't merely inherited.
 294     for base_cls in cls.__mro__[1:]:
 295         if anns is getattr(base_cls, "__annotations__", None):
 296             return {}
 297 
 298     return anns

 301 def _counter_getter(e):
 302     """
 303     Key function for sorting to avoid re-creating a lambda for every class.
 304     """
 305     return e[1].counter

 308 def _transform_attrs(cls, these, auto_attribs, kw_only):
 309     """
 310     Transform all `_CountingAttr`s on a class into `Attribute`s.
 311 
 312     If *these* is passed, use that and don't look for them on the class.
 313 
 314     Return an `_Attributes`.
 315     """
 316     cd = cls.__dict__
 317     anns = _get_annotations(cls)
 318 
 319     if these is not None:
 320         ca_list = [(name, ca) for name, ca in iteritems(these)]
 321 
 322         if not isinstance(these, ordered_dict):
 323             ca_list.sort(key=_counter_getter)
 324     elif auto_attribs is True:
 325         ca_names = {
 326             name
 327             for name, attr in cd.items()
 328             if isinstance(attr, _CountingAttr)
 329         }
 330         ca_list = []
 331         annot_names = set()
 332         for attr_name, type in anns.items():
 333             if _is_class_var(type):
 334                 continue
 335             annot_names.add(attr_name)
 336             a = cd.get(attr_name, NOTHING)
 337             if not isinstance(a, _CountingAttr):
 338                 if a is NOTHING:
 339                     a = attrib()
 340                 else:
 341                     a = attrib(default=a)
 342             ca_list.append((attr_name, a))
 343 
 344         unannotated = ca_names - annot_names
 345         if len(unannotated) > 0:
 346             raise UnannotatedAttributeError(
 347                 "The following `attr.ib`s lack a type annotation: "
 348                 + ", ".join(
 349                     sorted(unannotated, key=lambda n: cd.get(n).counter)
 350                 )
 351                 + "."
 352             )
 353     else:
 354         ca_list = sorted(
 355             (
 356                 (name, attr)
 357                 for name, attr in cd.items()
 358                 if isinstance(attr, _CountingAttr)
 359             ),
 360             key=lambda e: e[1].counter,
 361         )
 362 
 363     own_attrs = [
 364         Attribute.from_counting_attr(
 365             name=attr_name, ca=ca, type=anns.get(attr_name)
 366         )
 367         for attr_name, ca in ca_list
 368     ]
 369 
 370     base_attrs = []
 371     base_attr_map = {}  # A dictionary of base attrs to their classes.
 372     taken_attr_names = {a.name: a for a in own_attrs}
 373 
 374     # Traverse the MRO and collect attributes.
 375     for base_cls in cls.__mro__[1:-1]:
 376         sub_attrs = getattr(base_cls, "__attrs_attrs__", None)
 377         if sub_attrs is not None:
 378             for a in sub_attrs:
 379                 prev_a = taken_attr_names.get(a.name)
 380                 # Only add an attribute if it hasn't been defined before.  This
 381                 # allows for overwriting attribute definitions by subclassing.
 382                 if prev_a is None:
 383                     base_attrs.append(a)
 384                     taken_attr_names[a.name] = a
 385                     base_attr_map[a.name] = base_cls
 386 
 387     attr_names = [a.name for a in base_attrs + own_attrs]
 388 
 389     AttrsClass = _make_attr_tuple_class(cls.__name__, attr_names)
 390 
 391     if kw_only:
 392         own_attrs = [a._assoc(kw_only=True) for a in own_attrs]
 393         base_attrs = [a._assoc(kw_only=True) for a in base_attrs]
 394 
 395     attrs = AttrsClass(base_attrs + own_attrs)
 396 
 397     # Mandatory vs non-mandatory attr order only matters when they are part of
 398     # the __init__ signature and when they aren't kw_only (which are moved to
 399     # the end and can be mandatory or non-mandatory in any order, as they will
 400     # be specified as keyword args anyway). Check the order of those attrs:
 401     had_default = False
 402     for a in (a for a in attrs if a.init is not False and a.kw_only is False):
 403         if had_default is True and a.default is NOTHING:
 404             raise ValueError(
 405                 "No mandatory attributes allowed after an attribute with a "
 406                 "default value or factory.  Attribute in question: %r" % (a,)
 407             )
 408 
 409         if had_default is False and a.default is not NOTHING:
 410             had_default = True
 411 
 412     return _Attributes((attrs, base_attrs, base_attr_map))
 413

 429 class _ClassBuilder(object):
 430     """
 431     Iteratively build *one* class.
 432     """
 433 
 434     __slots__ = (
 435         "_cls",
 436         "_cls_dict",
 437         "_attrs",
 438         "_base_names",
 439         "_attr_names",
 440         "_slots",
 441         "_frozen",
 442         "_weakref_slot",
 443         "_cache_hash",
 444         "_has_post_init",
 445         "_delete_attribs",
 446         "_base_attr_map",
 447         "_is_exc",
 448     )
 449 
 450     def __init__(
 451         self,
 452         cls,
 453         these,
 454         slots,
 455         frozen,
 456         weakref_slot,
 457         auto_attribs,
 458         kw_only,
 459         cache_hash,
 460         is_exc,
 461     ):
 462         attrs, base_attrs, base_map = _transform_attrs(
 463             cls, these, auto_attribs, kw_only
 464         )
 465 
 466         self._cls = cls
 467         self._cls_dict = dict(cls.__dict__) if slots else {}
 468         self._attrs = attrs
 469         self._base_names = set(a.name for a in base_attrs)
 470         self._base_attr_map = base_map
 471         self._attr_names = tuple(a.name for a in attrs)
 472         self._slots = slots
 473         self._frozen = frozen or _has_frozen_base_class(cls)
 474         self._weakref_slot = weakref_slot
 475         self._cache_hash = cache_hash
 476         self._has_post_init = bool(getattr(cls, "__attrs_post_init__", False))
 477         self._delete_attribs = not bool(these)
 478         self._is_exc = is_exc
 479 
 480         self._cls_dict["__attrs_attrs__"] = self._attrs
 481 
 482         if frozen:
 483             self._cls_dict["__setattr__"] = _frozen_setattrs
 484             self._cls_dict["__delattr__"] = _frozen_delattrs
 485 
 486     def __repr__(self):
 487         return "<_ClassBuilder(cls={cls})>".format(cls=self._cls.__name__)
 488 
 489     def build_class(self):
 490         """
 491         Finalize class based on the accumulated configuration.
 492 
 493         Builder cannot be used after calling this method.
 494         """
 495         if self._slots is True:
 496             return self._create_slots_class()
 497         else:
 498             return self._patch_original_class()
 499 
 500     def _patch_original_class(self):
 501         """
 502         Apply accumulated methods and return the class.
 503         """
 504         cls = self._cls
 505         base_names = self._base_names
 506 
 507         # Clean class of attribute definitions (`attr.ib()`s).
 508         if self._delete_attribs:
 509             for name in self._attr_names:
 510                 if (
 511                     name not in base_names
 512                     and getattr(cls, name, _sentinel) is not _sentinel
 513                 ):
 514                     try:
 515                         delattr(cls, name)
 516                     except AttributeError:
 517                         # This can happen if a base class defines a class
 518                         # variable and we want to set an attribute with the
 519                         # same name by using only a type annotation.
 520                         pass
 521 
 522         # Attach our dunder methods.
 523         for name, value in self._cls_dict.items():
 524             setattr(cls, name, value)
 525 
 526         # Attach __setstate__. This is necessary to clear the hash code
 527         # cache on deserialization. See issue
 528         # https://github.com/python-attrs/attrs/issues/482 .
 529         # Note that this code only handles setstate for dict classes.
 530         # For slotted classes, see similar code in _create_slots_class .
 531         if self._cache_hash:
 532             existing_set_state_method = getattr(cls, "__setstate__", None)
 533             if existing_set_state_method:
 534                 raise NotImplementedError(
 535                     "Currently you cannot use hash caching if "
 536                     "you specify your own __setstate__ method."
 537                     "See https://github.com/python-attrs/attrs/issues/494 ."
 538                 )
 539 
 540             def cache_hash_set_state(chss_self, _):
 541                 # clear hash code cache
 542                 setattr(chss_self, _hash_cache_field, None)
 543 
 544             setattr(cls, "__setstate__", cache_hash_set_state)
 545 
 546         return cls
 547 
 548     def _create_slots_class(self):
 549         """
 550         Build and return a new class with a `__slots__` attribute.
 551         """
 552         base_names = self._base_names
 553         cd = {
 554             k: v
 555             for k, v in iteritems(self._cls_dict)
 556             if k not in tuple(self._attr_names) + ("__dict__", "__weakref__")
 557         }
 558 
 559         weakref_inherited = False
 560 
 561         # Traverse the MRO to check for an existing __weakref__.
 562         for base_cls in self._cls.__mro__[1:-1]:
 563             if "__weakref__" in getattr(base_cls, "__dict__", ()):
 564                 weakref_inherited = True
 565                 break
 566 
 567         names = self._attr_names
 568         if (
 569             self._weakref_slot
 570             and "__weakref__" not in getattr(self._cls, "__slots__", ())
 571             and "__weakref__" not in names
 572             and not weakref_inherited
 573         ):
 574             names += ("__weakref__",)
 575 
 576         # We only add the names of attributes that aren't inherited.
 577         # Settings __slots__ to inherited attributes wastes memory.
 578         slot_names = [name for name in names if name not in base_names]
 579         if self._cache_hash:
 580             slot_names.append(_hash_cache_field)
 581         cd["__slots__"] = tuple(slot_names)
 582 
 583         qualname = getattr(self._cls, "__qualname__", None)
 584         if qualname is not None:
 585             cd["__qualname__"] = qualname
 586 
 587         # __weakref__ is not writable.
 588         state_attr_names = tuple(
 589             an for an in self._attr_names if an != "__weakref__"
 590         )
 591 
 592         def slots_getstate(self):
 593             """
 594             Automatically created by attrs.
 595             """
 596             return tuple(getattr(self, name) for name in state_attr_names)
 597 
 598         hash_caching_enabled = self._cache_hash
 599 
 600         def slots_setstate(self, state):
 601             """
 602             Automatically created by attrs.
 603             """
 604             __bound_setattr = _obj_setattr.__get__(self, Attribute)
 605             for name, value in zip(state_attr_names, state):
 606                 __bound_setattr(name, value)
 607             # Clearing the hash code cache on deserialization is needed
 608             # because hash codes can change from run to run. See issue
 609             # https://github.com/python-attrs/attrs/issues/482 .
 610             # Note that this code only handles setstate for slotted classes.
 611             # For dict classes, see similar code in _patch_original_class .
 612             if hash_caching_enabled:
 613                 __bound_setattr(_hash_cache_field, None)
 614 
 615         # slots and frozen require __getstate__/__setstate__ to work
 616         cd["__getstate__"] = slots_getstate
 617         cd["__setstate__"] = slots_setstate
 618 
 619         # Create new class based on old class and our methods.
 620         cls = type(self._cls)(self._cls.__name__, self._cls.__bases__, cd)
 621 
 622         # The following is a fix for
 623         # https://github.com/python-attrs/attrs/issues/102.  On Python 3,
 624         # if a method mentions `__class__` or uses the no-arg super(), the
 625         # compiler will bake a reference to the class in the method itself
 626         # as `method.__closure__`.  Since we replace the class with a
 627         # clone, we rewrite these references so it keeps working.
 628         for item in cls.__dict__.values():
 629             if isinstance(item, (classmethod, staticmethod)):
 630                 # Class- and staticmethods hide their functions inside.
 631                 # These might need to be rewritten as well.
 632                 closure_cells = getattr(item.__func__, "__closure__", None)
 633             else:
 634                 closure_cells = getattr(item, "__closure__", None)
 635 
 636             if not closure_cells:  # Catch None or the empty list.
 637                 continue
 638             for cell in closure_cells:
 639                 if cell.cell_contents is self._cls:
 640                     set_closure_cell(cell, cls)
 641 
 642         return cls
 643

 645         self._cls_dict["__repr__"] = self._add_method_dunders(
 646             _make_repr(self._attrs, ns=ns)
 647         )
 648         return self

 651         repr = self._cls_dict.get("__repr__")
 652         if repr is None:
 653             raise ValueError(
 654                 "__str__ can only be generated if a __repr__ exists."
 655             )

 658             return self.__repr__()
 659 
 660         self._cls_dict["__str__"] = self._add_method_dunders(__str__)
 661         return self

 715     def _add_method_dunders(self, method):
 716         """
 717         Add __module__ and __qualname__ to a *method* if possible.
 718         """
 719         try:
 720             method.__module__ = self._cls.__module__
 721         except AttributeError:
 722             pass

 726                 (self._cls.__qualname__, method.__name__)

 734 _CMP_DEPRECATION = (
 735     "The usage of `cmp` is deprecated and will be removed on or after "
 736     "2021-06-01.  Please use `eq` and `order` instead."
 737 )

 740 def _determine_eq_order(cmp, eq, order):
 741     """
 742     Validate the combination of *cmp*, *eq*, and *order*. Derive the effective
 743     values of eq and order.
 744     """
 745     if cmp is not None and any((eq is not None, order is not None)):
 746         raise ValueError("Don't mix `cmp` with `eq' and `order`.")
 747 
 748     # cmp takes precedence due to bw-compatibility.
 749     if cmp is not None:
 750         warnings.warn(_CMP_DEPRECATION, DeprecationWarning, stacklevel=3)
 751 
 752         return cmp, cmp
 753 
 754     # If left None, equality is on and ordering mirrors equality.
 755     if eq is None:
 756         eq = True
 757 
 758     if order is None:
 759         order = eq
 760 
 761     if eq is False and order is True:
 762         raise ValueError("`order` can only be True if `eq` is True too.")
 763 
 764     return eq, order

 767 def attrs(
 768     maybe_cls=None,
 769     these=None,
 770     repr_ns=None,
 771     repr=True,
 772     cmp=None,
 773     hash=None,
 774     init=True,
 775     slots=False,
 776     frozen=False,
 777     weakref_slot=True,
 778     str=False,
 779     auto_attribs=False,
 780     kw_only=False,
 781     cache_hash=False,
 782     auto_exc=False,
 783     eq=None,
 784     order=None,
 785 ):
 786     r"""
 787     A class decorator that adds `dunder
 788     <https://wiki.python.org/moin/DunderAlias>`_\ -methods according to the
 789     specified attributes using `attr.ib` or the *these* argument.
 790 
 791     :param these: A dictionary of name to `attr.ib` mappings.  This is
 792         useful to avoid the definition of your attributes within the class body
 793         because you can't (e.g. if you want to add ``__repr__`` methods to
 794         Django models) or don't want to.
 795 
 796         If *these* is not ``None``, ``attrs`` will *not* search the class body
 797         for attributes and will *not* remove any attributes from it.
 798 
 799         If *these* is an ordered dict (`dict` on Python 3.6+,
 800         `collections.OrderedDict` otherwise), the order is deduced from
 801         the order of the attributes inside *these*.  Otherwise the order
 802         of the definition of the attributes is used.
 803 
 804     :type these: `dict` of `str` to `attr.ib`
 805 
 806     :param str repr_ns: When using nested classes, there's no way in Python 2
 807         to automatically detect that.  Therefore it's possible to set the
 808         namespace explicitly for a more meaningful ``repr`` output.
 809     :param bool repr: Create a ``__repr__`` method with a human readable
 810         representation of ``attrs`` attributes..
 811     :param bool str: Create a ``__str__`` method that is identical to
 812         ``__repr__``.  This is usually not necessary except for
 813         `Exception`\ s.
 814     :param bool eq: If ``True`` or ``None`` (default), add ``__eq__`` and
 815         ``__ne__`` methods that check two instances for equality.
 816 
 817         They compare the instances as if they were tuples of their ``attrs``
 818         attributes, but only iff the types of both classes are *identical*!
 819     :type eq: `bool` or `None`
 820     :param bool order: If ``True``, add ``__lt__``, ``__le__``, ``__gt__``,
 821         and ``__ge__`` methods that behave like *eq* above and allow instances
 822         to be ordered. If ``None`` (default) mirror value of *eq*.
 823     :type order: `bool` or `None`
 824     :param cmp: Setting to ``True`` is equivalent to setting ``eq=True,
 825         order=True``. Deprecated in favor of *eq* and *order*, has precedence
 826         over them for backward-compatibility though. Must not be mixed with
 827         *eq* or *order*.
 828     :type cmp: `bool` or `None`
 829     :param hash: If ``None`` (default), the ``__hash__`` method is generated
 830         according how *eq* and *frozen* are set.
 831 
 832         1. If *both* are True, ``attrs`` will generate a ``__hash__`` for you.
 833         2. If *eq* is True and *frozen* is False, ``__hash__`` will be set to
 834            None, marking it unhashable (which it is).
 835         3. If *eq* is False, ``__hash__`` will be left untouched meaning the
 836            ``__hash__`` method of the base class will be used (if base class is
 837            ``object``, this means it will fall back to id-based hashing.).
 838 
 839         Although not recommended, you can decide for yourself and force
 840         ``attrs`` to create one (e.g. if the class is immutable even though you
 841         didn't freeze it programmatically) by passing ``True`` or not.  Both of
 842         these cases are rather special and should be used carefully.
 843 
 844         See our documentation on `hashing`, Python's documentation on
 845         `object.__hash__`, and the `GitHub issue that led to the default \
 846         behavior <https://github.com/python-attrs/attrs/issues/136>`_ for more
 847         details.
 848     :type hash: ``bool`` or ``None``
 849     :param bool init: Create a ``__init__`` method that initializes the
 850         ``attrs`` attributes.  Leading underscores are stripped for the
 851         argument name.  If a ``__attrs_post_init__`` method exists on the
 852         class, it will be called after the class is fully initialized.
 853     :param bool slots: Create a `slotted class <slotted classes>` that's more
 854         memory-efficient.
 855     :param bool frozen: Make instances immutable after initialization.  If
 856         someone attempts to modify a frozen instance,
 857         `attr.exceptions.FrozenInstanceError` is raised.
 858 
 859         Please note:
 860 
 861             1. This is achieved by installing a custom ``__setattr__`` method
 862                on your class, so you can't implement your own.
 863 
 864             2. True immutability is impossible in Python.
 865 
 866             3. This *does* have a minor a runtime performance `impact
 867                <how-frozen>` when initializing new instances.  In other words:
 868                ``__init__`` is slightly slower with ``frozen=True``.
 869 
 870             4. If a class is frozen, you cannot modify ``self`` in
 871                ``__attrs_post_init__`` or a self-written ``__init__``. You can
 872                circumvent that limitation by using
 873                ``object.__setattr__(self, "attribute_name", value)``.
 874 
 875     :param bool weakref_slot: Make instances weak-referenceable.  This has no
 876         effect unless ``slots`` is also enabled.
 877     :param bool auto_attribs: If True, collect `PEP 526`_-annotated attributes
 878         (Python 3.6 and later only) from the class body.
 879 
 880         In this case, you **must** annotate every field.  If ``attrs``
 881         encounters a field that is set to an `attr.ib` but lacks a type
 882         annotation, an `attr.exceptions.UnannotatedAttributeError` is
 883         raised.  Use ``field_name: typing.Any = attr.ib(...)`` if you don't
 884         want to set a type.
 885 
 886         If you assign a value to those attributes (e.g. ``x: int = 42``), that
 887         value becomes the default value like if it were passed using
 888         ``attr.ib(default=42)``.  Passing an instance of `Factory` also
 889         works as expected.
 890 
 891         Attributes annotated as `typing.ClassVar`, and attributes that are
 892         neither annotated nor set to an `attr.ib` are **ignored**.
 893 
 894         .. _`PEP 526`: https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0526/
 895     :param bool kw_only: Make all attributes keyword-only (Python 3+)
 896         in the generated ``__init__`` (if ``init`` is ``False``, this
 897         parameter is ignored).
 898     :param bool cache_hash: Ensure that the object's hash code is computed
 899         only once and stored on the object.  If this is set to ``True``,
 900         hashing must be either explicitly or implicitly enabled for this
 901         class.  If the hash code is cached, avoid any reassignments of
 902         fields involved in hash code computation or mutations of the objects
 903         those fields point to after object creation.  If such changes occur,
 904         the behavior of the object's hash code is undefined.
 905     :param bool auto_exc: If the class subclasses `BaseException`
 906         (which implicitly includes any subclass of any exception), the
 907         following happens to behave like a well-behaved Python exceptions
 908         class:
 909 
 910         - the values for *eq*, *order*, and *hash* are ignored and the
 911           instances compare and hash by the instance's ids (N.B. ``attrs`` will
 912           *not* remove existing implementations of ``__hash__`` or the equality
 913           methods. It just won't add own ones.),
 914         - all attributes that are either passed into ``__init__`` or have a
 915           default value are additionally available as a tuple in the ``args``
 916           attribute,
 917         - the value of *str* is ignored leaving ``__str__`` to base classes.
 918 
 919     .. versionadded:: 16.0.0 *slots*
 920     .. versionadded:: 16.1.0 *frozen*
 921     .. versionadded:: 16.3.0 *str*
 922     .. versionadded:: 16.3.0 Support for ``__attrs_post_init__``.
 923     .. versionchanged:: 17.1.0
 924        *hash* supports ``None`` as value which is also the default now.
 925     .. versionadded:: 17.3.0 *auto_attribs*
 926     .. versionchanged:: 18.1.0
 927        If *these* is passed, no attributes are deleted from the class body.
 928     .. versionchanged:: 18.1.0 If *these* is ordered, the order is retained.
 929     .. versionadded:: 18.2.0 *weakref_slot*
 930     .. deprecated:: 18.2.0
 931        ``__lt__``, ``__le__``, ``__gt__``, and ``__ge__`` now raise a
 932        `DeprecationWarning` if the classes compared are subclasses of
 933        each other. ``__eq`` and ``__ne__`` never tried to compared subclasses
 934        to each other.
 935     .. versionchanged:: 19.2.0
 936        ``__lt__``, ``__le__``, ``__gt__``, and ``__ge__`` now do not consider
 937        subclasses comparable anymore.
 938     .. versionadded:: 18.2.0 *kw_only*
 939     .. versionadded:: 18.2.0 *cache_hash*
 940     .. versionadded:: 19.1.0 *auto_exc*
 941     .. deprecated:: 19.2.0 *cmp* Removal on or after 2021-06-01.
 942     .. versionadded:: 19.2.0 *eq* and *order*
 943     """
 944     eq, order = _determine_eq_order(cmp, eq, order)
 945 
 946     def wrap(cls):
 947 
 948         if getattr(cls, "__class__", None) is None:
 949             raise TypeError("attrs only works with new-style classes.")
 950 
 951         is_exc = auto_exc is True and issubclass(cls, BaseException)
 952 
 953         builder = _ClassBuilder(
 954             cls,
 955             these,
 956             slots,
 957             frozen,
 958             weakref_slot,
 959             auto_attribs,
 960             kw_only,
 961             cache_hash,
 962             is_exc,
 963         )
 964 
 965         if repr is True:
 966             builder.add_repr(repr_ns)
 967         if str is True:
 968             builder.add_str()
 969         if eq is True and not is_exc:
 970             builder.add_eq()
 971         if order is True and not is_exc:
 972             builder.add_order()
 973 
 974         if hash is not True and hash is not False and hash is not None:
 975             # Can't use `hash in` because 1 == True for example.
 976             raise TypeError(
 977                 "Invalid value for hash.  Must be True, False, or None."
 978             )
 979         elif hash is False or (hash is None and eq is False) or is_exc:
 980             # Don't do anything. Should fall back to __object__'s __hash__
 981             # which is by id.
 982             if cache_hash:
 983                 raise TypeError(
 984                     "Invalid value for cache_hash.  To use hash caching,"
 985                     " hashing must be either explicitly or implicitly "
 986                     "enabled."
 987                 )
 988         elif hash is True or (hash is None and eq is True and frozen is True):
 989             # Build a __hash__ if told so, or if it's safe.
 990             builder.add_hash()
 991         else:
 992             # Raise TypeError on attempts to hash.
 993             if cache_hash:
 994                 raise TypeError(
 995                     "Invalid value for cache_hash.  To use hash caching,"
 996                     " hashing must be either explicitly or implicitly "
 997                     "enabled."
 998                 )
 999             builder.make_unhashable()
1000 
1001         if init is True:
1002             builder.add_init()
1003         else:
1004             if cache_hash:
1005                 raise TypeError(
1006                     "Invalid value for cache_hash.  To use hash caching,"
1007                     " init must be True."
1008                 )
1009 
1010         return builder.build_class()
1011 
1012     # maybe_cls's type depends on the usage of the decorator.  It's a class
1013     # if it's used as `@attrs` but ``None`` if used as `@attrs()`.
1014     if maybe_cls is None:
1015         return wrap
1016     else:
1017         return wrap(maybe_cls)

1058 def _generate_unique_filename(cls, func_name):
1059     """
1060     Create a "filename" suitable for a function being generated.
1061     """
1062     unique_id = uuid.uuid4()
1063     extra = ""
1064     count = 1
1065 
1066     while True:
1067         unique_filename = "<attrs generated {0} {1}.{2}{3}>".format(
1068             func_name,
1069             cls.__module__,
1070             getattr(cls, "__qualname__", cls.__name__),
1071             extra,
1072         )
1073         # To handle concurrency we essentially "reserve" our spot in
1074         # the linecache with a dummy line.  The caller can then
1075         # set this value correctly.
1076         cache_line = (1, None, (str(unique_id),), unique_filename)
1077         if (
1078             linecache.cache.setdefault(unique_filename, cache_line)
1079             == cache_line
1080         ):
1081             return unique_filename
1082 
1083         # Looks like this spot is taken. Try again.
1084         count += 1
1085         extra = "-{0}".format(count)

1088 def _make_hash(cls, attrs, frozen, cache_hash):
1089     attrs = tuple(
1090         a for a in attrs if a.hash is True or (a.hash is None and a.eq is True)
1091     )
1092 
1093     tab = "        "
1094 
1095     unique_filename = _generate_unique_filename(cls, "hash")
1096     type_hash = hash(unique_filename)
1097 
1098     method_lines = ["def __hash__(self):"]
1099 
1100     def append_hash_computation_lines(prefix, indent):
1101         """
1102         Generate the code for actually computing the hash code.
1103         Below this will either be returned directly or used to compute
1104         a value which is then cached, depending on the value of cache_hash
1105         """
1106         method_lines.extend(
1107             [indent + prefix + "hash((", indent + "        %d," % (type_hash,)]
1108         )
1109 
1110         for a in attrs:
1111             method_lines.append(indent + "        self.%s," % a.name)
1112 
1113         method_lines.append(indent + "    ))")
1114 
1115     if cache_hash:
1116         method_lines.append(tab + "if self.%s is None:" % _hash_cache_field)
1117         if frozen:
1118             append_hash_computation_lines(
1119                 "object.__setattr__(self, '%s', " % _hash_cache_field, tab * 2
1120             )
1121             method_lines.append(tab * 2 + ")")  # close __setattr__
1122         else:
1123             append_hash_computation_lines(
1124                 "self.%s = " % _hash_cache_field, tab * 2
1125             )
1126         method_lines.append(tab + "return self.%s" % _hash_cache_field)
1127     else:
1128         append_hash_computation_lines("return ", tab)
1129 
1130     script = "\n".join(method_lines)
1131     globs = {}
1132     locs = {}
1133     bytecode = compile(script, unique_filename, "exec")
1134     eval(bytecode, globs, locs)
1135 
1136     # In order of debuggers like PDB being able to step through the code,
1137     # we add a fake linecache entry.
1138     linecache.cache[unique_filename] = (
1139         len(script),
1140         None,
1141         script.splitlines(True),
1142         unique_filename,
1143     )
1144 
1145     return locs["__hash__"]

1156 def __ne__(self, other):
1157     """
1158     Check equality and either forward a NotImplemented or return the result
1159     negated.
1160     """
1161     result = self.__eq__(other)
1162     if result is NotImplemented:
1163         return NotImplemented
1164 
1165     return not result

1168 def _make_eq(cls, attrs):
1169     attrs = [a for a in attrs if a.eq]
1170 
1171     unique_filename = _generate_unique_filename(cls, "eq")
1172     lines = [
1173         "def __eq__(self, other):",
1174         "    if other.__class__ is not self.__class__:",
1175         "        return NotImplemented",
1176     ]
1177     # We can't just do a big self.x = other.x and... clause due to
1178     # irregularities like nan == nan is false but (nan,) == (nan,) is true.
1179     if attrs:
1180         lines.append("    return  (")
1181         others = ["    ) == ("]
1182         for a in attrs:
1183             lines.append("        self.%s," % (a.name,))
1184             others.append("        other.%s," % (a.name,))
1185 
1186         lines += others + ["    )"]
1187     else:
1188         lines.append("    return True")
1189 
1190     script = "\n".join(lines)
1191     globs = {}
1192     locs = {}
1193     bytecode = compile(script, unique_filename, "exec")
1194     eval(bytecode, globs, locs)
1195 
1196     # In order of debuggers like PDB being able to step through the code,
1197     # we add a fake linecache entry.
1198     linecache.cache[unique_filename] = (
1199         len(script),
1200         None,
1201         script.splitlines(True),
1202         unique_filename,
1203     )
1204     return locs["__eq__"], __ne__

1208     attrs = [a for a in attrs if a.order]

1210     def attrs_to_tuple(obj):

1216     def __lt__(self, other):
1217         """
1218         Automatically created by attrs.
1219         """
1220         if other.__class__ is self.__class__:
1221             return attrs_to_tuple(self) < attrs_to_tuple(other)
1222 
1223         return NotImplemented
1224 
1225     def __le__(self, other):
1226         """
1227         Automatically created by attrs.
1228         """
1229         if other.__class__ is self.__class__:
1230             return attrs_to_tuple(self) <= attrs_to_tuple(other)
1231 
1232         return NotImplemented
1233 
1234     def __gt__(self, other):
1235         """
1236         Automatically created by attrs.
1237         """
1238         if other.__class__ is self.__class__:
1239             return attrs_to_tuple(self) > attrs_to_tuple(other)
1240 
1241         return NotImplemented

1248             return attrs_to_tuple(self) >= attrs_to_tuple(other)

1284     def __repr__(self):
1285         """
1286         Automatically created by attrs.
1287         """
1288         try:
1289             working_set = _already_repring.working_set
1290         except AttributeError:
1291             working_set = set()
1292             _already_repring.working_set = working_set
1293 
1294         if id(self) in working_set:
1295             return "..."
1296         real_cls = self.__class__
1297         if ns is None:
1298             qualname = getattr(real_cls, "__qualname__", None)
1299             if qualname is not None:
1300                 class_name = qualname.rsplit(">.", 1)[-1]
1301             else:
1302                 class_name = real_cls.__name__
1303         else:
1304             class_name = ns + "." + real_cls.__name__
1305 
1306         # Since 'self' remains on the stack (i.e.: strongly referenced) for the
1307         # duration of this call, it's safe to depend on id(...) stability, and
1308         # not need to track the instance and therefore worry about properties
1309         # like weakref- or hash-ability.
1310         working_set.add(id(self))
1311         try:
1312             result = [class_name, "("]
1313             first = True
1314             for name, attr_repr in attr_names_with_reprs:
1315                 if first:
1316                     first = False
1317                 else:
1318                     result.append(", ")
1319                 result.extend(
1320                     (name, "=", attr_repr(getattr(self, name, NOTHING)))
1321                 )
1322             return "".join(result) + ")"
1323         finally:
1324             working_set.remove(id(self))
1325 
1326     return __repr__
1327

1329 def _add_repr(cls, ns=None, attrs=None):
1330     """
1331     Add a repr method to *cls*.
1332     """
1333     if attrs is None:
1334         attrs = cls.__attrs_attrs__
1335 
1336     cls.__repr__ = _make_repr(attrs, ns)
1337     return cls

1340 def _make_init(
1341     cls, attrs, post_init, frozen, slots, cache_hash, base_attr_map, is_exc
1342 ):
1343     attrs = [a for a in attrs if a.init or a.default is not NOTHING]
1344 
1345     unique_filename = _generate_unique_filename(cls, "init")
1346 
1347     script, globs, annotations = _attrs_to_init_script(
1348         attrs, frozen, slots, post_init, cache_hash, base_attr_map, is_exc
1349     )
1350     locs = {}
1351     bytecode = compile(script, unique_filename, "exec")
1352     attr_dict = dict((a.name, a) for a in attrs)
1353     globs.update({"NOTHING": NOTHING, "attr_dict": attr_dict})
1354 
1355     if frozen is True:
1356         # Save the lookup overhead in __init__ if we need to circumvent
1357         # immutability.
1358         globs["_cached_setattr"] = _obj_setattr
1359 
1360     eval(bytecode, globs, locs)
1361 
1362     # In order of debuggers like PDB being able to step through the code,
1363     # we add a fake linecache entry.
1364     linecache.cache[unique_filename] = (
1365         len(script),
1366         None,
1367         script.splitlines(True),
1368         unique_filename,
1369     )
1370 
1371     __init__ = locs["__init__"]
1372     __init__.__annotations__ = annotations
1373 
1374     return __init__

1377 def fields(cls):
1378     """
1379     Return the tuple of ``attrs`` attributes for a class.
1380 
1381     The tuple also allows accessing the fields by their names (see below for
1382     examples).
1383 
1384     :param type cls: Class to introspect.
1385 
1386     :raise TypeError: If *cls* is not a class.
1387     :raise attr.exceptions.NotAnAttrsClassError: If *cls* is not an ``attrs``
1388         class.
1389 
1390     :rtype: tuple (with name accessors) of `attr.Attribute`
1391 
1392     ..  versionchanged:: 16.2.0 Returned tuple allows accessing the fields
1393         by name.
1394     """
1395     if not isclass(cls):
1396         raise TypeError("Passed object must be a class.")
1397     attrs = getattr(cls, "__attrs_attrs__", None)
1398     if attrs is None:
1399         raise NotAnAttrsClassError(
1400             "{cls!r} is not an attrs-decorated class.".format(cls=cls)
1401         )
1402     return attrs

1405 def fields_dict(cls):
1406     """
1407     Return an ordered dictionary of ``attrs`` attributes for a class, whose
1408     keys are the attribute names.
1409 
1410     :param type cls: Class to introspect.
1411 
1412     :raise TypeError: If *cls* is not a class.
1413     :raise attr.exceptions.NotAnAttrsClassError: If *cls* is not an ``attrs``
1414         class.
1415 
1416     :rtype: an ordered dict where keys are attribute names and values are
1417         `attr.Attribute`\\ s. This will be a `dict` if it's
1418         naturally ordered like on Python 3.6+ or an
1419         :class:`~collections.OrderedDict` otherwise.
1420 
1421     .. versionadded:: 18.1.0
1422     """
1423     if not isclass(cls):
1424         raise TypeError("Passed object must be a class.")
1425     attrs = getattr(cls, "__attrs_attrs__", None)
1426     if attrs is None:
1427         raise NotAnAttrsClassError(
1428             "{cls!r} is not an attrs-decorated class.".format(cls=cls)
1429         )
1430     return ordered_dict(((a.name, a) for a in attrs))

1461 def _attrs_to_init_script(
1462     attrs, frozen, slots, post_init, cache_hash, base_attr_map, is_exc
1463 ):
1464     """
1465     Return a script of an initializer for *attrs* and a dict of globals.
1466 
1467     The globals are expected by the generated script.
1468 
1469     If *frozen* is True, we cannot set the attributes directly so we use
1470     a cached ``object.__setattr__``.
1471     """
1472     lines = []
1473     any_slot_ancestors = any(
1474         _is_slot_attr(a.name, base_attr_map) for a in attrs
1475     )
1476     if frozen is True:
1477         if slots is True:
1478             lines.append(
1479                 # Circumvent the __setattr__ descriptor to save one lookup per
1480                 # assignment.
1481                 # Note _setattr will be used again below if cache_hash is True
1482                 "_setattr = _cached_setattr.__get__(self, self.__class__)"
1483             )
1484 
1485             def fmt_setter(attr_name, value_var):
1486                 return "_setattr('%(attr_name)s', %(value_var)s)" % {
1487                     "attr_name": attr_name,
1488                     "value_var": value_var,
1489                 }
1490 
1491             def fmt_setter_with_converter(attr_name, value_var):
1492                 conv_name = _init_converter_pat.format(attr_name)
1493                 return "_setattr('%(attr_name)s', %(conv)s(%(value_var)s))" % {
1494                     "attr_name": attr_name,
1495                     "value_var": value_var,
1496                     "conv": conv_name,
1497                 }
1498 
1499         else:
1500             # Dict frozen classes assign directly to __dict__.
1501             # But only if the attribute doesn't come from an ancestor slot
1502             # class.
1503             # Note _inst_dict will be used again below if cache_hash is True
1504             lines.append("_inst_dict = self.__dict__")
1505             if any_slot_ancestors:
1506                 lines.append(
1507                     # Circumvent the __setattr__ descriptor to save one lookup
1508                     # per assignment.
1509                     "_setattr = _cached_setattr.__get__(self, self.__class__)"
1510                 )
1511 
1512             def fmt_setter(attr_name, value_var):
1513                 if _is_slot_attr(attr_name, base_attr_map):
1514                     res = "_setattr('%(attr_name)s', %(value_var)s)" % {
1515                         "attr_name": attr_name,
1516                         "value_var": value_var,
1517                     }
1518                 else:
1519                     res = "_inst_dict['%(attr_name)s'] = %(value_var)s" % {
1520                         "attr_name": attr_name,
1521                         "value_var": value_var,
1522                     }
1523                 return res
1524 
1525             def fmt_setter_with_converter(attr_name, value_var):
1526                 conv_name = _init_converter_pat.format(attr_name)
1527                 if _is_slot_attr(attr_name, base_attr_map):
1528                     tmpl = "_setattr('%(attr_name)s', %(c)s(%(value_var)s))"
1529                 else:
1530                     tmpl = "_inst_dict['%(attr_name)s'] = %(c)s(%(value_var)s)"
1531                 return tmpl % {
1532                     "attr_name": attr_name,
1533                     "value_var": value_var,
1534                     "c": conv_name,
1535                 }
1536 
1537     else:
1538         # Not frozen.
1539         def fmt_setter(attr_name, value):
1540             return "self.%(attr_name)s = %(value)s" % {
1541                 "attr_name": attr_name,
1542                 "value": value,
1543             }
1544 
1545         def fmt_setter_with_converter(attr_name, value_var):
1546             conv_name = _init_converter_pat.format(attr_name)
1547             return "self.%(attr_name)s = %(conv)s(%(value_var)s)" % {
1548                 "attr_name": attr_name,
1549                 "value_var": value_var,
1550                 "conv": conv_name,
1551             }
1552 
1553     args = []
1554     kw_only_args = []
1555     attrs_to_validate = []
1556 
1557     # This is a dictionary of names to validator and converter callables.
1558     # Injecting this into __init__ globals lets us avoid lookups.
1559     names_for_globals = {}
1560     annotations = {"return": None}
1561 
1562     for a in attrs:
1563         if a.validator:
1564             attrs_to_validate.append(a)
1565         attr_name = a.name
1566         arg_name = a.name.lstrip("_")
1567         has_factory = isinstance(a.default, Factory)
1568         if has_factory and a.default.takes_self:
1569             maybe_self = "self"
1570         else:
1571             maybe_self = ""
1572         if a.init is False:
1573             if has_factory:
1574                 init_factory_name = _init_factory_pat.format(a.name)
1575                 if a.converter is not None:
1576                     lines.append(
1577                         fmt_setter_with_converter(
1578                             attr_name,
1579                             init_factory_name + "({0})".format(maybe_self),
1580                         )
1581                     )
1582                     conv_name = _init_converter_pat.format(a.name)
1583                     names_for_globals[conv_name] = a.converter
1584                 else:
1585                     lines.append(
1586                         fmt_setter(
1587                             attr_name,
1588                             init_factory_name + "({0})".format(maybe_self),
1589                         )
1590                     )
1591                 names_for_globals[init_factory_name] = a.default.factory
1592             else:
1593                 if a.converter is not None:
1594                     lines.append(
1595                         fmt_setter_with_converter(
1596                             attr_name,
1597                             "attr_dict['{attr_name}'].default".format(
1598                                 attr_name=attr_name
1599                             ),
1600                         )
1601                     )
1602                     conv_name = _init_converter_pat.format(a.name)
1603                     names_for_globals[conv_name] = a.converter
1604                 else:
1605                     lines.append(
1606                         fmt_setter(
1607                             attr_name,
1608                             "attr_dict['{attr_name}'].default".format(
1609                                 attr_name=attr_name
1610                             ),
1611                         )
1612                     )
1613         elif a.default is not NOTHING and not has_factory:
1614             arg = "{arg_name}=attr_dict['{attr_name}'].default".format(
1615                 arg_name=arg_name, attr_name=attr_name
1616             )
1617             if a.kw_only:
1618                 kw_only_args.append(arg)
1619             else:
1620                 args.append(arg)
1621             if a.converter is not None:
1622                 lines.append(fmt_setter_with_converter(attr_name, arg_name))
1623                 names_for_globals[
1624                     _init_converter_pat.format(a.name)
1625                 ] = a.converter
1626             else:
1627                 lines.append(fmt_setter(attr_name, arg_name))
1628         elif has_factory:
1629             arg = "{arg_name}=NOTHING".format(arg_name=arg_name)
1630             if a.kw_only:
1631                 kw_only_args.append(arg)
1632             else:
1633                 args.append(arg)
1634             lines.append(
1635                 "if {arg_name} is not NOTHING:".format(arg_name=arg_name)
1636             )
1637             init_factory_name = _init_factory_pat.format(a.name)
1638             if a.converter is not None:
1639                 lines.append(
1640                     "    " + fmt_setter_with_converter(attr_name, arg_name)
1641                 )
1642                 lines.append("else:")
1643                 lines.append(
1644                     "    "
1645                     + fmt_setter_with_converter(
1646                         attr_name,
1647                         init_factory_name + "({0})".format(maybe_self),
1648                     )
1649                 )
1650                 names_for_globals[
1651                     _init_converter_pat.format(a.name)
1652                 ] = a.converter
1653             else:
1654                 lines.append("    " + fmt_setter(attr_name, arg_name))
1655                 lines.append("else:")
1656                 lines.append(
1657                     "    "
1658                     + fmt_setter(
1659                         attr_name,
1660                         init_factory_name + "({0})".format(maybe_self),
1661                     )
1662                 )
1663             names_for_globals[init_factory_name] = a.default.factory
1664         else:
1665             if a.kw_only:
1666                 kw_only_args.append(arg_name)
1667             else:
1668                 args.append(arg_name)
1669             if a.converter is not None:
1670                 lines.append(fmt_setter_with_converter(attr_name, arg_name))
1671                 names_for_globals[
1672                     _init_converter_pat.format(a.name)
1673                 ] = a.converter
1674             else:
1675                 lines.append(fmt_setter(attr_name, arg_name))
1676 
1677         if a.init is True and a.converter is None and a.type is not None:
1678             annotations[arg_name] = a.type
1679 
1680     if attrs_to_validate:  # we can skip this if there are no validators.
1681         names_for_globals["_config"] = _config
1682         lines.append("if _config._run_validators is True:")
1683         for a in attrs_to_validate:
1684             val_name = "__attr_validator_{}".format(a.name)
1685             attr_name = "__attr_{}".format(a.name)
1686             lines.append(
1687                 "    {}(self, {}, self.{})".format(val_name, attr_name, a.name)
1688             )
1689             names_for_globals[val_name] = a.validator
1690             names_for_globals[attr_name] = a
1691     if post_init:
1692         lines.append("self.__attrs_post_init__()")
1693 
1694     # because this is set only after __attrs_post_init is called, a crash
1695     # will result if post-init tries to access the hash code.  This seemed
1696     # preferable to setting this beforehand, in which case alteration to
1697     # field values during post-init combined with post-init accessing the
1698     # hash code would result in silent bugs.
1699     if cache_hash:
1700         if frozen:
1701             if slots:
1702                 # if frozen and slots, then _setattr defined above
1703                 init_hash_cache = "_setattr('%s', %s)"
1704             else:
1705                 # if frozen and not slots, then _inst_dict defined above
1706                 init_hash_cache = "_inst_dict['%s'] = %s"
1707         else:
1708             init_hash_cache = "self.%s = %s"
1709         lines.append(init_hash_cache % (_hash_cache_field, "None"))
1710 
1711     # For exceptions we rely on BaseException.__init__ for proper
1712     # initialization.
1713     if is_exc:
1714         vals = ",".join("self." + a.name for a in attrs if a.init)
1715 
1716         lines.append("BaseException.__init__(self, %s)" % (vals,))
1717 
1718     args = ", ".join(args)
1719     if kw_only_args:
1720         if PY2:
1721             raise PythonTooOldError(
1722                 "Keyword-only arguments only work on Python 3 and later."
1723             )
1724 
1725         args += "{leading_comma}*, {kw_only_args}".format(
1726             leading_comma=", " if args else "",
1727             kw_only_args=", ".join(kw_only_args),
1728         )
1729     return (
1730         """\
1731 def __init__(self, {args}):
1732     {lines}
1733 """.format(
1734             args=args, lines="\n    ".join(lines) if lines else "pass"
1735         ),
1736         names_for_globals,
1737         annotations,
1738     )

2071 def make_class(name, attrs, bases=(object,), **attributes_arguments):
2072     """
2073     A quick way to create a new class called *name* with *attrs*.
2074 
2075     :param name: The name for the new class.
2076     :type name: str
2077 
2078     :param attrs: A list of names or a dictionary of mappings of names to
2079         attributes.
2080 
2081         If *attrs* is a list or an ordered dict (`dict` on Python 3.6+,
2082         `collections.OrderedDict` otherwise), the order is deduced from
2083         the order of the names or attributes inside *attrs*.  Otherwise the
2084         order of the definition of the attributes is used.
2085     :type attrs: `list` or `dict`
2086 
2087     :param tuple bases: Classes that the new class will subclass.
2088 
2089     :param attributes_arguments: Passed unmodified to `attr.s`.
2090 
2091     :return: A new class with *attrs*.
2092     :rtype: type
2093 
2094     .. versionadded:: 17.1.0 *bases*
2095     .. versionchanged:: 18.1.0 If *attrs* is ordered, the order is retained.
2096     """
2097     if isinstance(attrs, dict):
2098         cls_dict = attrs
2099     elif isinstance(attrs, (list, tuple)):
2100         cls_dict = dict((a, attrib()) for a in attrs)
2101     else:
2102         raise TypeError("attrs argument must be a dict or a list.")
2103 
2104     post_init = cls_dict.pop("__attrs_post_init__", None)
2105     type_ = type(
2106         name,
2107         bases,
2108         {} if post_init is None else {"__attrs_post_init__": post_init},
2109     )
2110     # For pickling to work, the __module__ variable needs to be set to the
2111     # frame where the class is created.  Bypass this step in environments where
2112     # sys._getframe is not defined (Jython for example) or sys._getframe is not
2113     # defined for arguments greater than 0 (IronPython).
2114     try:
2115         type_.__module__ = sys._getframe(1).f_globals.get(
2116             "__name__", "__main__"
2117         )
2118     except (AttributeError, ValueError):
2119         pass
2120 
2121     # We do it here for proper warnings with meaningful stacklevel.
2122     cmp = attributes_arguments.pop("cmp", None)
2123     attributes_arguments["eq"], attributes_arguments[
2124         "order"
2125     ] = _determine_eq_order(
2126         cmp, attributes_arguments.get("eq"), attributes_arguments.get("order")
2127     )
2128 
2129     return _attrs(these=cls_dict, **attributes_arguments)(type_)

2150     """
2151     A validator that composes multiple validators into one.
2152

2160     vals = []
2161     for validator in validators:

2163             validator._validators
2164             if isinstance(validator, _AndValidator)
